<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>36</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=center>&nbsp;<B><U>Report of Management on Internal Control Over Financial Reporting</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial"><B>The Board of Directors and Stockholders</B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial"><B>American Independence Corp.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The management of American Independence Corp. (&quot;AMIC&quot;) is responsible for establishing and maintaining adequate internal control over financial reporting. AMIC's internal control system was designed to provide reasonable assurance to the Company's management and Board of Directors regarding reliability of financial reporting and the preparation and fair presentation of published financial statements for external purposes in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>All internal control systems, no matter how well designed, have inherent limitations. Therefore, even those systems determined to be effective can provide only reasonable assurance with respect to financial statement preparation and presentation. &nbsp;Also, projections of any evaluation of effectiveness to future periods are subject to the risk that controls may become inadequate because of changes in conditions, or that the degree of compliance with the policies or procedures may deteriorate.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Management assessed the effectiveness of AMIC's internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2005. In making this assessment, management used the criteria set forth by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO) in <I>Internal Control &#150;Integrated Framework</I>. Based on our assessment we concluded that, as of December 31, 2005, AMIC's internal control over financial reporting is effective.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>KPMG LLP, the independent registered public accounting firm that audited the financial statements in this Annual Report, has issued an attestation report on management's assessment of, and the effective operation of, AMIC's internal control over financial reporting as of December&nbsp;31, 2005, which is included herein on page 38.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>37</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=center><B><U>Report of Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial"><B>The Board of Directors and Stockholders</B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial"><B>American Independence Corp.:</B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>We have audited management's assessment, included in the accompanying &#147;Report of Management on Internal Control Over Financial Reporting&#148;, that American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries maintained effective internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2005, based on criteria established in Internal Control &#150; Integrated Framework issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO). The Company's management is responsible for maintaining effective internal control over financial reporting and for its assessment of the effectiveness of internal control over financial reporting. Our responsibility is to express an opinion on management's assessment and an opinion on the effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting based on our audit.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>We conducted our audit in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States). Those standards require that we plan and perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether effective internal control over financial reporting was maintained in all material respects. Our audit included obtaining an understanding of internal control over financial reporting, evaluating management's assessment, testing and evaluating the design and operating effectiveness of internal control, and performing such other procedures as we considered necessary in the circumstances. We believe that our audit provides a reasonable basis for our opinion.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>A company's internal control over financial reporting is a process designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation of financial statements for external purposes in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles. &nbsp;A company's internal control over financial reporting includes those policies and procedures that (1) pertain to the maintenance of records that, in reasonable detail, accurately and fairly reflect the transactions and dispositions of the assets of the company; (2) provide reasonable assurance that transactions are recorded as necessary to permit preparation of financial statements in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles, and that receipts and expenditures of the company are being made only in accordance with authorizations of management and directors of the company; and (3) provide reasonable assurance regarding prevention or timel
y detection of unauthorized acquisition, use, or disposition of the company&#146;s assets that could have a material effect on the financial statements. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Because of its inherent limitations, internal control over financial reporting may not prevent or detect misstatements. &nbsp;Also, projections of any evaluation of effectiveness to future periods are subject to the risk that controls may become inadequate because of changes in conditions, or that the degree of compliance with the policies or procedures may deteriorate.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In our opinion, management's assessment that American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries maintained effective internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2005, is fairly stated, in all material respects, based on criteria established in Internal Control &#150; Integrated Framework issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO). &nbsp;Also, in our opinion, American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries maintained, in all material respects, effective internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2005, based on criteria established in Internal Control &#150; Integrated Framework issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO).</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>38</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>We also have audited, in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States), the consolidated balance sheets of American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries as of December 31, 2005 and 2004, and the related consolidated statements of operations, stockholders&#146; equity, and cash flows for each of the years in the three-year period ended December 31, 2005, and our report dated March 13, 2006 expressed an unqualified opinion on those consolidated financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>/s/ KPMG LLP</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>New York, New York </P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>March 13, 2006</P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10.85pt" align=center><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>39</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10.85pt; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=center><B><U>&nbsp;Report of Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial"><B>The Board of Directors and Stockholders</B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial"><B>American Independence Corp.:</B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:5pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>We have audited the accompanying consolidated balance sheets of American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries as of December 31, 2005 and 2004, and the related consolidated statements of operations, stockholders&#146; equity, and cash flows for each of the years in the three-year period ended December 31, 2005. In connection with our audits of the consolidated financial statements, we have also audited the financial statement schedules listed in the accompanying index. &nbsp;These consolidated financial statements and financial statement schedules are the responsibility of the Company&#146;s management. Our responsibility is to express an opinion on these consolidated financial statements and financial statement schedules based on our audits.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:5pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>We conducted our audits in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States). &nbsp;Those standards require that we plan and perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements are free of material misstatement. &nbsp;An audit includes examining, on a test basis, evidence supporting the amounts and disclosures in the financial statements. An audit also includes assessing the accounting principles used and significant estimates made by management, as well as evaluating the overall financial statement presentation. &nbsp;We believe that our audits provide a reasonable basis for our opinion.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:5pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In our opinion, the consolidated financial statements referred to above present fairly, in all material respects, the financial position of American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries as of December 31, 2005 and 2004, and the results of their operations and their cash flows for each of the years in the three-year period ended December 31, 2005, in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles. &nbsp;Also in our opinion, the related financial statement schedules, when considered in relation to the basic consolidated financial statements taken as a whole, present fairly, in all material respects, the information set forth therein.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:5pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>We also have audited, in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States), the effectiveness of American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries&#146; internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2005, based on criteria established in Internal Control &#150; Integrated Framework issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO), and our report dated March 13, 2006 expressed an unqualified opinion on management&#146;s assessment of, and the effective operation of, internal control over financial reporting.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:5pt"><BR></P>

<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>44</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=center><B>American Independence Corp. and Subsidiaries</B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:-12pt; padding-left:18pt; text-indent:-18pt; font-family:Arial"><B>1.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; padding-left:18pt; font-family:Arial"><B>Nature of Business</B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>American Independence Corp. (&quot;AMIC&quot; or &quot;the Company&quot;) is a holding company engaged in the insurance and reinsurance business through its wholly-owned insurance company, Independence American Insurance Company (&quot;Independence American&quot;) and its managing general underwriter subsidiaries: IndependenceCare Holdings L.L.C. and its subsidiaries (collectively referred to as &quot;IndependenceCare&quot;); Risk Assessment Strategies, Inc. (&quot;RAS&quot;), Marlton Risk Group LLC (&quot;Marlton&quot;), and its investment in Majestic Underwriters LLC (&quot;Majestic&quot;). IndependenceCare, RAS and Marlton are collectively referred to as the &quot;MGU Subsidiaries&quot;.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Prior to November 14, 2002, the Company (then known as SoftNet Systems, Inc.) was a holding company principally engaged in providing Internet services. &nbsp;Four previously reported business segments, business center services, satellite-based Internet services, cable-based Internet services and document management, have ceased operations or have been sold, and accordingly are reported as discontinued operations (see Note 9 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Since November 2002, AMIC has been affiliated with Independence Holding Company (&quot;IHC&quot;), an insurance holding company, which held 48% of AMIC&#146;s outstanding common stock at December 31, 2005. &nbsp;The senior management of IHC provides direction to the Company through a service agreement between the Company and IHC. &nbsp;IHC has also entered into long-term reinsurance treaties to cede Medical Stop-Loss to the Company. &nbsp;Additionally, the Company began reinsuring IHC&#146;s New York statutory disability business in the third quarter of 2004 and IHC&#146;s short-term medical and consumer-driven group major medical business in 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:-12pt; padding-left:18pt; text-indent:-18pt; font-family:Arial"><B>2.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; padding-left:18pt; font-family:Arial"><B>Summary of Significant Accounting Policies</B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial"><B><I>Principles of Consolidation and Presentation of Financial Statements</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The consolidated financial statements have been prepared in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles and include the accounts of AMIC and its consolidated subsidiaries. All intercompany transactions have been eliminated in consolidation. The preparation of financial statements in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect: &nbsp;(i) the reported amounts of assets and liabilities; (ii) the disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements; and (iii) the reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting period. Actual results could differ from those estimates.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial"><B><I>Reclassifications</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Certain reclassifications have been made to prior years' consolidated financial statements and related notes to the consolidated financial statements in order to conform to the current year presentation.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial"><B><I>Reverse Split</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On February 13, 2003, the shareholders of the Company voted in favor of a one-for-three reverse stock split. &nbsp;The purpose of the reverse stock split was to increase the Company's stock price to over $5.00 per share in order to avoid a delisting of the Company's common stock from the Nasdaq National Market. Although currently listed on the NASDAQ National Market, the Company was required to comply with NASDAQ's initial listing requirements because of the discontinuation of its prior business and acquisition of its current insurance operations. &nbsp;The effect of the reverse split </P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>45</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>has been reflected in all periods in the accompanying consolidated financial statements and notes thereto.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Investment in</I></B><I> </I><B><I>Majestic Underwriters LLC</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:45.8pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company's investment in Majestic Underwriters LLC (see Note 5) (&quot;Majestic&quot;) is carried on the equity method with the Company's share of income or loss credited or charged, as appropriate, to the Consolidated Statement of Operations with a corresponding charge to the Company's investment account. The Company also reduces its investment account for its proportionate share of the amortization expense for the intangible assets recorded in the acquisition.</P>
<P style="margin-top:5pt; margin-bottom:5pt; font-family:Arial"><B><I>Goodwill and Other Intangibles </I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:5pt; margin-bottom:5pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Goodwill and intangible assets with indefinite lives, which consist of licenses, are not amortized but are reviewed for impairment, on a reporting unit basis, at least annually, or more frequently if indicators arise. The Company defines its reporting units on a segment basis.</P>
<P style="margin-top:4.15pt; margin-bottom:4.15pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>For goodwill, if the book value of a reporting unit exceeds its fair value, the implied fair value of goodwill is compared with the carrying amount of goodwill. If the carrying amount of goodwill exceeds the implied fair value, an impairment loss is recorded in an amount equal to that excess.</P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company's intangible assets consisting of broker/third party relationships are amortized over five years.</P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Impairment of Long-Lived Assets</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company evaluates long-lived assets for impairment annually or whenever current events or changes in circumstances warrant evaluating whether the carrying value of an asset may not be recoverable based on expected undiscounted cash flows attributable to that asset. &nbsp;The amount of any impairment is measured as the difference between the carrying value and the fair value of the impaired asset.</P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Fair Value of Financial Instruments</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The carrying amount of the Company's financial instruments, which include cash and cash equivalents, restricted cash, short-term investments, due from reinsurers and premiums receivable approximates their fair values.</P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Cash, Cash Equivalents and Restricted Cash</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Cash and cash equivalents consist of cash and highly liquid securities with maturities of three months or less from date of purchase. &nbsp;Restricted cash primarily consists of funds held by the MGUs for the benefit of their insurers and reinsurers. &nbsp;These funds are restricted and are to be used to facilitate expeditious payment of approved claims. &nbsp;The funds are replenished by the insurers and reinsurers as claims are paid by the MGUs.</P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Short-Term Investments</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Investments with original maturities of 91-days to 1 year are considered short-term investments and are carried at cost which approximates fair value.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>46</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Securities Purchased Under Agreements to Resell and Securities Sold Under Agreements to Repurchase</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Securities purchased under agreements to resell (&quot;resale agreements&quot;) and securities sold under agreements to repurchase (&quot;repurchase agreements&quot;) are treated as financing transactions and are carried at the amounts at which the securities will be subsequently resold or repurchased as specified in the agreements.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Investment Securities</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(i)</B> Investments in fixed income securities, redeemable preferred stock equity securities and derivatives (options and options on future contracts) are accounted for as follows:</P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:72pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(a)</B> Securities which are held for trading purposes are carried at estimated fair value (&quot;fair value&quot;). &nbsp;Unrealized gains or losses are credited or charged, as appropriate, to the Consolidated Statements of Operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:72pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(b)</B> Securities which may or may not be held to maturity (&quot;available-for-sale securities&quot;) are carried at fair value. Unrealized gains or losses are credited or charged, as appropriate, directly to accumulated other comprehensive income (a component of stockholders' equity). Realized gains and losses on sales of available-for-sale securities, and unrealized losses considered to be other than temporary, are credited or charged to the Consolidated Statements of Operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(ii)</B> Financial instruments sold, but not yet purchased, represent obligations to replace borrowed securities that have been sold. &nbsp;Such transactions occur in anticipation of declines in the fair value of the securities. The Company's risk is an increase in the fair value of the securities sold in excess of the consideration received, but that risk is mitigated as a result of relationships to certain securities owned. &nbsp;Unrealized gains or losses on open transactions are credited or charged, as appropriate, to the Consolidated Statements of Operations. &nbsp;While the transaction is open, the Company will also incur an expense for any accrued dividends or interest payable to the lender of the securities. &nbsp;When the transaction is closed, the Company realizes a gain or loss in an amount equal to the difference between the price at which the securities were sold and the cost of replacing the borrowed securities.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(iii)</B> Gains or losses on sales of securities are determined on the basis of specific identification.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(iv) </B>The Company enters into derivative financial instruments, such as put and call option contracts and options on interest rate futures contracts, to minimize losses on portions of the Company's fixed income portfolio in a rapidly changing interest rate environment. &nbsp;Equity index options are entered into to offset price fluctuations in the equity markets. These derivative financial instruments are all readily marketable and are carried on the Consolidated Balance Sheets at their current fair value with changes in fair value (unrealized gains or losses), credited or charged, as appropriate, to the Consolidated Statements of Operations. All realized gains and losses are reflected currently in the Consolidated Statements of Operations. There were no such derivatives outstanding at December 31, 2005 and 2004. Gains and (losses) on these instruments were ($90,000), ($27,000) and $45,000 during 2005, 2004 and 2003, respectively.
</P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(v) </B>Fair value is determined by quoted market prices, where available, or by independent pricing services.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(vi)</B>The Company reviews its investment securities regularly and determines whether other than temporary impairments have occurred. If a decline in fair value is judged by management to be other than temporary, a loss is recognized by a charge to the Consolidated Statements of Operations, establishing a new cost basis for the security. &nbsp;The factors considered by management in its regular review include, but are not limited to:&nbsp; the length of time and extent to which the fair value has been less than cost; the financial condition and near-term prospects of the issuer; adverse changes in ratings announced by one or more rating agencies; whether the issuer of a debt security has remained current on principal and interest payments; whether the decline in fair value appears to be issuer specific or, alternatively, a reflection of general market or industry conditions; and the Company's intent and ability to hold the security 
for a period of time sufficient to </P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>47</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>allow for a recovery in fair value. &nbsp;For securities within the scope of Emerging Issues Task Force Issue 99-20, such as purchased interest-only securities, an impairment loss is recognized when there has been a decrease in expected cash flows combined with a decline in the security's fair value below cost.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Fixed Assets</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Fixed assets are stated at cost net of accumulated depreciation. &nbsp;Improvements are capitalized while repair and maintenance costs are charged to operations as incurred. &nbsp;Depreciation of property and equipment has been provided on the straight-line method over the estimated useful lives of the respective assets (3 years for computer equipment and 10 years for furniture and fixtures). &nbsp;Amortization of leasehold improvements has been provided on the straight-line method over the shorter of the lease term or the estimated useful life of the asset.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Premium and MGU Fee Income Revenue Recognition</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Direct and assumed premiums from short-duration contracts are recognized as revenue over the period of the contracts in proportion to the amount of insurance protection provided. &nbsp;The Company records MGU fee income as policy premium payments are earned. &nbsp;MGUs are compensated in two ways. &nbsp;They earn fee income based on the volume of business produced, and collect profit-sharing commissions if such business exceeds certain profitability benchmarks. Profit-sharing commissions are accounted for beginning in the period in which the Company believes they are reasonably estimable, which is typically at the point that claims have developed to a level where Claim Development Patterns can be applied to generate reasonably reliable estimates of ultimate claim levels. Profit-sharing commissions are a function of an MGU attaining certain profitability thresholds and could greatly vary from quarter to quarter.</
P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>MGU fee income consisted of the following:</P>

<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Insurance Reserves </I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company maintains loss reserves to cover its estimated liability for unpaid losses and loss adjustment expenses, including legal, other fees, and costs not associated with specific claims but related to the claims payment function), for reported and unreported claims incurred as of the end of each accounting period. &nbsp;These loss reserves are based on actuarial assumptions and are maintained at levels that are in accordance with US generally accepted accounting principles. &nbsp;Many factors could affect these reserves, including economic and social conditions, frequency and severity of claims, medical trend resulting from the influences of underlying cost inflation, changes in utilization and demand for medical services, and changes in doctrines of legal liability and damage awards in litigation. Therefore, the Company&#146;s reserves are necessarily based on estimates, assumptions and analysis of historical experience. The Comp
any&#146;s results depend upon the variation between actual claims experience and the assumptions used in determining reserves and pricing products. Reserve assumptions and estimates require significant judgment and, </P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>48</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>therefore, are inherently uncertain. The Company cannot determine with precision the ultimate amounts that will be paid for actual claims or the timing of those payments. The Company's estimate of loss represents management's estimate of the Company's liability at the balance sheet date.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>All of the Company&#146;s contracts are short-duration and are accounted for based on actuarial estimates of the amount of loss inherent in that period&#146;s claims, including losses incurred for claims that have not been reported (&#147;IBNR&#148;). Short-duration contract loss estimates rely on actuarial observations of ultimate loss experience for similar historical events. </P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Liabilities for insurance reserves on short-term medical and disability coverages are computed using claim development patterns and projected loss ratios derived from actual historical premium and claim data. Reserves for medical stop-loss insurance are more volatile in nature than those for fully insured medical insurance.&nbsp; This is primarily due to the excess nature of medical stop-loss, with very high deductibles applying to specific claims on any individual claimant and in the aggregate for a given group.&nbsp; The level of these deductibles makes it more difficult to predict the amount and payment pattern of such claims.&nbsp; Furthermore, these excess claims are highly sensitive to changes in factors such as medical trend, provider contracts and medical treatment protocols, adding to the difficulty in predicting claim values and estimating reserves.&nbsp; Also, because medical stop-loss is in excess of an underlying benefit pl
an, there is an additional layer of claim reporting and processing that can affect claim payment patterns.&nbsp; Finally, changes in the distribution of business by effective month can affect reserve estimates due to the lag time required to accumulate claims against the stop-loss deductible, unlike fully insured medical which has a more predictable lag pattern.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Liabilities for insurance reserves for fully insured medical business are established to provide for the liability for incurred but not paid claims.&nbsp; Reserves are calculated using standard actuarial methods and practices.&nbsp; Historical paid claim patterns are reviewed and estimated development factors applied to immature incurred months to calculate these reserves.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>While these calculations are based on standard methodologies, they are estimates based on historical patterns.&nbsp; To the extent that actual claim payment patterns differ from historical patterns, such estimated reserves may be redundant or inadequate. &nbsp;The effects of such deviations are evaluated by considering claim backlog statistics and reviewing the reasonableness of projected claim ratios.&nbsp; Other factors which may affect the accuracy of reserve estimates include the proportion of large claims which may take longer to adjudicate, changes in billing patterns by providers and changes in claim management practices such as hospital bill audits.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Management believes that the Company's methods of estimating the liabilities for insurance reserves provided appropriate levels of reserves at December 31, 2005 and December 31, 2004. Changes in the Company's reserve estimates are recorded through a charge or credit to its earnings.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Reinsurance</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Amounts recoverable or paid for under reinsurance contracts are included in total assets or total liabilities as due from reinsurers or due to reinsurers.</P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Income Taxes</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company accounts for income taxes under the asset and liability method<I>.</I> Deferred tax assets and liabilities are recognized for the future tax consequences attributable to differences between the financial carrying amounts of existing assets and liabilities and their respective tax basis, and operating loss and tax credit carry forwards. &nbsp;Deferred tax assets and liabilities are measured using enacted tax rates expected to apply to taxable income in the years in which those temporary differences are expected to be recovered or settled. &nbsp;The effect on deferred tax assets </P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>49</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>and liabilities of a change in tax rates is recognized in income in the period that includes the enactment date. Valuation allowances are established when necessary to reduce deferred tax assets where it is more likely than not that the deferred tax asset will not be realized (see Note 14 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Stock-Based Compensation and Change in Accounting Principle</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Effective October 1, 2002, the Company adopted certain provisions of Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 123, &quot;Accounting for Stock-Based Compensation&quot;(&quot;SFAS 123&quot;). SFAS 123 established a fair-value-based method of accounting for stock-based compensation plans. &nbsp;Pursuant to the transition provisions of SFAS 123, the Company applied the fair value method of accounting to all option grants issued on or after October 1, 2002. &nbsp;The fair value method was not applied to stock option awards granted prior to October 1, 2002. &nbsp;Such awards continued to be accounted for under the intrinsic value method pursuant to APB 25, except to the extent those prior years' awards were modified subsequent to October 1, 2002. &nbsp;At December 31, 2005 all such shares accounted for under APB 25 were fully vested or expired.</P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Income Per Common Share</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Basic income per common share is computed using the weighted average number of common stock shares outstanding during the period. &nbsp;Diluted income per common share is computed using the weighted average number of common stock shares and common stock equivalent shares outstanding during the period. &nbsp;Common stock equivalents consist of stock options (using the &quot;treasury stock&quot; method). &nbsp;Common Stock equivalent shares are excluded from the computation if the effect is anti-dilutive. &nbsp;As a result of the anti-dilutive effect, common stock equivalent shares have been excluded from the computation of diluted earnings per share for periods presented with a net loss. &nbsp;Included in the diluted earnings per share calculation for fiscal years 2005, 2004 and 2003, are 79,000, 101,000 and 54,000 shares, respectively, from the assumed exercise of options using the treasury stock method. &nbsp;Ne
t income does not change as a result of the assumed dilution of options.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Recent Accounting Pronouncements</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In May 2005, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (the &quot;FASB&quot;) issued SFAS No. 154, &quot;Accounting Changes and Error Corrections,&quot; which replaces APB Opinion No. 20, &quot;Accounting Changes,&quot; and SFAS No. 3, &quot;Reporting Accounting Changes in Interim Financial Statement,&quot; and changes the requirements for the accounting for and reporting of a change in accounting principle. SFAS No. 154 applies to all voluntary changes in accounting principle and to changes required by an accounting pronouncement when the pronouncement does not include specific transition provisions. SFAS No. 154 requires retrospective application of changes in accounting principle to prior periods' financial statements unless it is impracticable to determine either the period-specific effects or the cumulative effect of the change. APB Opinion No. 20 previously required that most voluntary changes in accounting principle be recognized 
by including the cumulative effect of the change in net income for the period of the change in accounting principle. &nbsp;SFAS No. 154 carries forward without change the guidance contained in APB Opinion No. 20 for reporting the correction of an error in previously issued financial statements and a change in accounting estimate. SFAS No. 154 also carries forward the guidance in APB Opinion No. 20 requiring justification of a change in accounting principle on the basis of preferability. SFAS No. 154 is effective for accounting changes and corrections of errors made in fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2005, with early adoption permitted. </P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>FASB Staff Position No. FAS 115-1 and FAS 124-1, &quot;The Meaning of Other-Than-Temporary Impairment and Its Application to Certain Investments&quot; (the &quot;FSP&quot;), was issued in November 2005 and addresses the determination of when an investment is considered impaired; whether the impairment is other than temporary; and how to measure an impairment loss. The FSP also addresses accounting considerations subsequent to the recognition of an other-than-</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>50</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>temporary impairment loss on a debt security, and requires certain disclosures about unrealized losses that have not been recognized as other-than-temporary impairments. The FSP replaces the impairment guidance in EITF Issue No. 03-1 with references to existing authoritative literature concerning other-than-temporary determinations (principally SFAS No. 115 and SEC Staff Accounting Bulletin 59). Under the FSP, an impairment loss must be recognized in earnings in an amount equal to the entire difference between the security's cost and its fair value at the financial statement date, without considering partial recoveries subsequent to that date. The FSP also requires that an investor recognize an other-than-temporary impairment loss when a decision to sell a security has been made and the investor does not expect the fair value of the security to fully recover prior to the expected time of sale. The FSP is effective for reporting 
periods beginning after December 15, 2005. The Company does not expect that the application of the FSP will have a material impact on its financial condition, results of operations or financial statement disclosures.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In December 2004, the FASB issued SFAS No. 123 (revised 2004) (&quot;SFAS No. 123R&quot;), &quot;Share-Based Payment&quot; which revised SFAS No. 123, &quot;Accounting for Stock-Based Compensation. This statement supercedes APB Opinion No. 25, &quot;Accounting for Stock Issued to Employees.&quot; SFAS No. 123R addresses the accounting for share-based payment transactions with employees and other third parties, eliminates the ability to account for share-based compensation transactions using APB 25 and requires that the compensation costs relating to such transactions be recognized in the consolidated statement of operations. The revised statement is effective as of the first fiscal year beginning after June 15, 2005. The Company already applies the fair value based method of accounting for all stock based compensation issued after October 1, 2002. &nbsp;At December 31, 2005 all such shares accounted for under APB 25 were fully vested or
 expired. The Company's adoption of SFAS No. 123R is not expected to have any impact on its financial condition or results of operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>3. &nbsp;Goodwill </I></B></P>

<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="line-height:normal; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial"><B>5<I>. &nbsp;Acquisitions</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:5pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Majestic</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:5pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Effective July 1, 2004,&nbsp;a wholly-owned subsidiary of the Company acquired a 23% interest in Majestic Underwriters LLC (&quot;Majestic&quot;), a Medical Stop-Loss managing general underwriter for a purchase price of $1,610,000. &nbsp;Concurrently, wholly-owned subsidiaries of Independence Holding&nbsp;Company&nbsp;acquired a 52% interest in Majestic. &nbsp;The senior management of Majestic owns the remaining 25% interest. &nbsp;The Company accounts for this investment using the equity method of accounting. &nbsp;This acquisition resulted in a $522,000 reduction of valuation allowance related to the deferred tax assets, with the effect being an increase to deferred tax asset and a corresponding decrease in other investments. &nbsp;Under certain circumstances set forth in the Limited Liability Agreement of Majestic, the Company has the right and/or obligation to purchase some or all of the minority interest in M
ajestic.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial"><B><I>ICH-MidAtlantic</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:5pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On April 16, 2004, the Company expanded its business through the acquisition of substantially all of the assets of an employer Medical Stop-Loss managing general underwriter for a purchase price of $600,000. &nbsp;The assets were acquired by IndependenceCare Underwriting </P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:5pt" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>52</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:5pt; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>Services&#150;MidAtlantic LLC (&quot;ICH-MidAtlantic&quot;), which is based in Baltimore, Maryland and which retained the key marketing personnel of the former MGU. &nbsp;This acquisition resulted in goodwill in the amount of $486,000 and intangible assets in the amount of $114,000.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:5pt" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial"><B><I>Marlton</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On February 10, 2003, but effective as of January 1, 2003, the Company acquired 80% of the business of an employer Medical Stop-Loss MGU and an affiliated entity (the &quot;Acquired MGUs&quot;). The acquisition was accomplished by the formation of Voorhees Risk Management LLC d.b.a. Marlton Risk Group (&quot;Marlton&quot;) into which the Acquired MGUs contributed all of their assets, and the Company contributed $16,000,000 cash for an 80% ownership interest. &nbsp;The Company's cash contribution was then distributed to the Acquired MGUs together with the remaining 20% interest in Marlton, and Marlton assumed all of the liabilities of the Acquired MGUs. Under certain circumstances set forth in the Limited Liability Company Agreement of Marlton, the Company has the right and/or obligation to purchase some or all of the minority interests in Marlton. The total purchase price of approximately $16,102,000 consisted of $16,000,000 of cash and
 $102,000 of direct transaction costs.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<TABLE style="font-size:10pt" cellspacing=0 align=center><TR><TD width=12.1></TD><TD width=268></TD><TD width=13.8></TD><TD width=16.4></TD><TD width=77.25></TD></TR>

<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Of the total purchase price, $5,323,000 has been allocated to net tangible assets acquired and $2,800,000 has been allocated to amortizable intangible assets acquired. &nbsp;The depreciation and amortization related to the fair value adjustment to net tangible assets and the amortization related to the amortizable intangible assets are reflected in the consolidated statements of operations. The intangible asset is being written off over the five years following the acquisition based on the respective discounted cash flows.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Of the total purchase price, approximately $11,373,000 has been allocated to goodwill. Goodwill represents the excess of the purchase price of an acquired business over the fair value of the underlying net tangible and intangible assets.</P>

<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; padding-right:-0.5pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Government-sponsored enterprise mortgage-backed securities consist of Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation and Federal National Mortgage Association securities.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:5pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:5pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The amortized cost and fair value of fixed maturities at December 31, 2005 by contractual maturity are shown below. &nbsp;Expected maturities will differ from contractual maturities because borrowers may have the right to call or prepay obligations with or without call or prepayment penalties. &nbsp;The average life of mortgage backed securities is affected by prepayments on the underlying loans and, therefore, is materially shorter than the original stated maturity.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:5pt" align=justify><BR>

<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Substantially all of the unrealized losses at December 31, 2005 and 2004 relate to investment grade securities and are attributable to changes in market interest rates subsequent to purchase. &nbsp;The Company reviews its investments regularly and monitors its investments for impairments. &nbsp;A total of 52 securities were in a continuous unrealized loss position for less than 12 months and 21 securities for 12 months or longer as of December 2005. &nbsp;A total of 46 securities were in a continuous unrealized loss position for less than 12 months and 4 securities for 12 months or longer as of December 31, 2004. &nbsp;For years 2005, 2004, and 2003 the Company realized a loss of $0, $134,000 and $0, respectively, from other than temporary impairments. &nbsp;The remaining unrealized losses were evaluated in accordance with the Company's policy and were determined to be temporary in nature at December 31, 2005. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>55</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>The Company had no derivative instruments at December 31, 2005 and December 31, 2004.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Gross gains of $478,000 and gross losses of $481,000 were realized on sales of available-for-sale securities for the year ended December 31, 2005. &nbsp;The Company realized gains of $248,000 from trading securities in fiscal year 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Gross gains of $876,000 and gross losses of $903,000 (including $134,000 from temporary impairment) were realized on sales of available-for-sale securities for the year ended December 31, 2004. &nbsp;The Company realized gains of $249,000 from trading securities in fiscal year 2004.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:5pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Gross gains of $1,449,000 and gross losses of $1,119,000 were realized on sales of available-for-sale securities for the year ended December 31, 2003.</P>

<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>7. &nbsp;Equity Investments</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>At December 31, 2005 and December 31, 2004, the Company had an equity investment in Majestic with a carrying value of $1,082,000 and 1,125,000, respectively (see Note 5). &nbsp;For fiscal years 2005 and 2004, the Company recorded $26,000 and $34,000, respectively, for its share of income from its investment in Majestic. &nbsp;In prior periods, the Company had various equity method investments. &nbsp;At December 31, 2003, the Company had written off or sold all prior investments held under the equity method of accounting.</P>

<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial"><B>9. &nbsp;Discontinued Operations</B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Until April 2002, the Company (then known as SoftNet Systems, Inc.) was an Internet service provider. &nbsp;Due to difficult and deteriorating conditions in that market, the Company discontinued this business. &nbsp;In December 2000, the Company's board of directors approved a plan to discontinue the operations of its subsidiary, ISP Channel, Inc., which had provided cable-based Internet access and related services, and the operations of another subsidiary, Aerzone Corporation, which provided Internet and related services at airports. &nbsp;In April 2002, the Company, ceased operations of its remaining operating subsidiary, Intelligent Communications, Inc., following the disposition of its key assets. &nbsp;The operating results of these discontinued operations have been segregated from continuing operations and are reported as a gain or loss from discontinued operations on the consolidated statements of operations. &nbsp;Although it is
 difficult to predict the final results, the gain or loss on disposition from discontinued operations includes management's estimates of costs to wind down the business and costs to settle its outstanding liabilities. &nbsp;The actual results could differ from these estimates. &nbsp;The net liabilities associated with discontinued operations are reflected in net liabilities associated with discontinued operations in the accompanying consolidated balance sheets.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I>Discontinued Operations of Intelligent Communications, Inc. (&quot;Intellicom&quot;)</I></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On March 29, 2002, the Company and its wholly-owned subsidiary, Intellicom, entered into an agreement to sell its operating business and certain assets to Loral Cyberstar, Inc. &nbsp;Following the sale of its operating business and certain assets to Loral Cyberstar, Inc., the Company's Board of Directors unanimously agreed to cease the operations of Intellicom on April 3, 2002. Principally due to the Company's guaranty of Intellicom's lease for its facility in Livermore, California, the Company has reserves for discontinued operations of Intellicom of $808,000 for this liability at December 31, 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I>Discontinued Operations of Aerzone Corporation (&quot;Aerzone&quot;)</I></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On January 24, 2000, the Company founded Aerzone (formerly SoftNet Zone, Inc.) to provide high-speed Internet access to global business travelers. &nbsp;As part of the Aerzone business, the Company acquired Laptop Lane, on April 21, 2000. &nbsp;On December 19, 2000, the Company decided to discontinue the Aerzone business in light of significant long-term capital needs and the difficulty of securing the necessary financing because of the current state of the financial markets. &nbsp;The Company has no remaining reserve for Aerzone at December 31, 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>57</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify><I>Discontinued Operations of ISP Channel, Inc. (&quot;ISP Channel&quot;)</I></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On December 7, 2000, the Company's Board of Directors approved a plan to discontinue providing cable-based Internet services through its ISP Channel subsidiary by December 31, 2000, because consolidation in the cable television industry made it difficult for ISP Channel to achieve the economies of scale necessary to provide such services profitably, and the Company was no longer able to bear the costs of maintaining the ISP Channel. &nbsp;The Company has no remaining reserve for ISP Channel at December 31, 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I>Discontinued Operations of Micrographic Technology Corporation (&quot;MTC&quot;)</I></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>As a result of the December 31, 1999 sale of MTC to Global Information Distribution GmbH (&quot;GID&quot;), the Company discontinued operations of MTC. &nbsp;The Company has no remaining reserve for MTC at December 31, 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I>Discontinued Operations of Kansas Communications, Inc (&quot;KCI&quot;)</I></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>As a result of the February 12, 1999 sale of the assets of the telecommunications segment, KCI, to Convergent Communications Services, Inc., the Company discontinued this segment. &nbsp;The Company has no remaining reserve for KCI at December 31, 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>10. &nbsp;Restructuring Reserve</B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On December 28, 2000, the Company&#146;s Board of Directors approved a plan to reduce its corporate headquarters staff in conjunction with discontinuing certain businesses. &nbsp;During the year ended December 31, 2005, the Company reversed the remaining reserve of $67,000 related to the restructuring. &nbsp;This reserve primarily related to the lease obligations of the former corporate headquarters in San Francisco, California, which expired on July 31, 2005; the Company also had an $800,000 security deposit with respect to this liability which was returned to the Company in August 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The balance of restructuring reserve as of December 31, 2005 and December 31, 2004, and activity during that period is as follows (in thousands):</P>

<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company has operating leases for office space and certain other office equipment. &nbsp;These operating leases provide for minimum rents and generally include options to renew for additional periods. &nbsp;The Company has subleased its principal executive offices.</P>

<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Legal Proceedings </I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial">The Company is involved in legal proceedings and claims which arise in the ordinary course of its businesses. The Company has established reserves that it believes are sufficient given information presently available related to its outstanding legal proceedings and claims. The Company believes the results of pending legal proceedings and claims are not expected to have a material adverse effect on its financial condition or cash flows, although there could be such an effect on its results of operations for a particular period.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>12. &nbsp;Stock Options and Warrants</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>1998 Stock Incentive Plan (&quot;1998 Plan&quot;)</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Effective October 1, 1998, the Company implemented the 1998 Plan, which the Company's stockholders approved on April 13, 1999. &nbsp;The 1998 Plan provides for the grants of non-statutory and incentive stock options, stock appreciation rights, restricted stock awards, performance shares, and other awards to officers, employee and other individuals. &nbsp;Under the terms of the 1998 Plan, stock options have a maximum term of ten years from the date of grant, and have various vesting criteria depending on the grant with most grants vesting 25% on the first year anniversary date of the grant and ratably over the next 36 months. &nbsp;In addition, the number of common stock shares reserved for issuance under the 1998 Plan will automatically increase on the first trading day of each calendar year, beginning in calendar year 2000, by an amount equal to four percent of the total number of common stock shares outstanding
 on the last trading day of the preceding calendar year, but in no event will any such annual increase exceed 666,666 shares, subject to adjustment for subsequent stock splits, stock dividends and similar transactions. &nbsp;At December 31, 2005, a total of 2,831,251 stock shares are reserved for issuance under the 1998 Plan. &nbsp;At December 31, 2005, stock options for 504,167 common stock shares were outstanding, stock options for 364,477 common stock shares were vested, and 4,814,307 common stock shares remained available for future stock options grants and other awards.</P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Common Stock Warrants</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On March 22, 1999, the Company issued warrants to purchase 1,004 common stock shares to an institutional lender in connection with a $3,000,000 credit facility. The credit facility was used to fund certain capital equipment acquisitions. &nbsp;The warrants had an exercise price of $89.63 and expired on March 22, 2003. &nbsp;The fair value of the warrants on the issuance date was estimated using the Black-Scholes option pricing model with the following assumptions: volatility of </P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>60</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>108%, risk free interest rate of 4.78%, no dividend yield, and an expected contractual life of four years.</P>

<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial"><B><I>Stock-Based Compensation and Change in Accounting Principle </I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On November 14, 2002, the Company adopted certain provisions of Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 123, &quot;Accounting for Stock-Based Compensation&quot; (&quot;SFAS 123&quot;). &nbsp;SFAS 123 established a fair-value-based method of accounting for stock-based compensation plans. &nbsp;Pursuant to the transition provisions of SFAS 123, the Company applied the fair value method of accounting to all option grants issued on or after October 1, 2002. &nbsp;The fair value method was not applied to stock option awards granted prior to October 1, 2002. &nbsp;Such awards continue to be accounted for under the intrinsic value method pursuant to APB 25, except to the extent those prior years' awards are modified subsequent to October 1, 2002. &nbsp;At December 31, 2005 all such shares accounted for under APB 25 were fully vested or expired. &nbsp;The Company recorded an expense of approximately $227,000, $456,000 and $123,000 for t
he years ended December 31, 2005, 2004 and 2003, respectively, related to options issued under the fair value based method. &nbsp;For the year ended December 31, 2003 the remaining $17,000 of non-cash compensation expense relates to options issued under the intrinsic value method pursuant to APB 25.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>62</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Had the Company applied the fair value based method of accounting for stock-based compensation awards issued prior to October 1, 2002, the Company's net income (loss) and income (loss) per share would have been the pro forma amounts as follows (in thousands except per share data):</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>13. &nbsp;Related Party Transactions</B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>AMIC and its subsidiaries incurred expense of $564,000, $550,000 and $201,000 for the twelve months ended December 31, 2005, 2004, and 2003 respectively, from its service agreements with IHC and its subsidiaries. &nbsp;These payments reimburse IHC and its subsidiaries, at agreed upon rates including an overhead factor, for management services provided to AMIC and its subsidiaries, including accounting, legal, compliance, underwriting, and claims.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; padding-right:-11.5pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Independence American assumes premiums from related parties, and records related insurance income, expenses, assets and liabilities. &nbsp;Additionally, the MGU Subsidiaries market, underwrite and provide administrative services (including premium collection, medical management and claims adjudication) for a substantial portion of the Medical Stop-Loss business written by the insurance subsidiaries of IHC and records related income, assets and liabilities in connection with that business. &nbsp;Such related party information is disclosed on the Consolidated Balance Sheets and Consolidated Statements of Operations. &nbsp;The Company also contracts for several types of insurance coverage (e.g. directors and officers and professional liability coverage) jointly with IHC. &nbsp;The cost of </P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>63</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; padding-right:-11.5pt; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>this coverage is split proportionally between the Company and IHC according to the type of risk and AMIC&#146;s portion is recorded in Selling, General and Administrative Expenses.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; padding-right:-11.5pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>14. &nbsp;Income Taxes</B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company and its subsidiaries file a consolidated Federal income tax return on a September 30 fiscal tax year. &nbsp;The provision (benefit) for income taxes for the periods ended December 31, 2005, 2004 and 2003 are as follows:</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Federal income tax provision (benefit) for the periods ending December 31, 2005, 2004 and 2003 include income tax provisions of $1,861,000, $3,155,000 and $969,000, respectively, for the utilization of the Company's Federal net operating loss carryforwards (NOLs). During 2005, the Company recorded $31,000 of deferred tax benefit on discontinued operations which was included in Gain (loss) on Disposition of Discontinued Operations, net of tax, in the Statement of Operations.</P>

<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>During the year ended December 31, 2005 the Company reduced its valuation allowance by $1,807,000. &nbsp;This reduction included $2,079,000 for the projected utilization of Federal operating losses which was allocated to operations and a $272,000 increase of deferred tax on unrealized losses allocated to equity. &nbsp;During the year ended December 31, 2004, the Company reduced its valuation allowance by $797,000. &nbsp;This reduction included $522,000 for the Majestic purchase transaction, which was allocated to goodwill and $275,000 for the net change in other deferred tax assets and liabilities. During the year ended December 31, 2003, the Company reduced its valuation allowance by $12,548,000. &nbsp;This reduction included $5,760,000 for the Marlton purchase transaction which was allocated to goodwill and $6,788,000 for the projected utilization of Federal net operating losses which was allocated to operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In assessing the realizability of deferred tax assets, management considers whether it is more likely than not that some portion or all of the deferred tax assets will not be realized. The ultimate realization of deferred tax assets is dependent upon the generation of future taxable income during the period in which those temporary differences become deductible. Management considers the scheduled reversal of deferred tax liabilities, projected future taxable income, and tax planning strategies in making this assessment. Management believes that it is more likely than not that the Company will realize the benefits of these net deferred tax assets recorded at December 31, 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR>

<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>At December 31, 2005, the Company also had net operating loss carryforwards of approximately $25,814,000 for state income tax purposes, primarily in the State of California. &nbsp;Management believes that it is more likely than not that the state tax benefit of these net operating loss carryforwards will not be realized.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>AMIC's ability to utilize its Federal Net Operating Loss Carrryforwards (&quot;NOLs&quot;) would be substantially reduced if AMIC were to undergo an &quot;ownership change&quot; within the meaning of Section 382(g)(1) of the Internal Revenue Code. AMIC will be treated as having had an &quot;ownership change&quot; if there is more than a 50% increase in stock ownership during a three year '&quot;testing period&quot; by &quot;5% stockholders.&quot; &nbsp;In order to reduce the risk of an ownership change, in November 2002, AMIC's stockholders approved an amendment to its Certificate of Incorporation restricting transfers of shares of its common stock that could result in the imposition of limitations on the use, for federal, state and city income tax purposes, of AMIC's carryforwards of net operating losses and certain federal income tax credits. &nbsp;The Certificate of Incorporation generally restricts any person from attempting to sell
, transfer or dispose, or purchase or acquire any AMIC stock, if such transfer would affect the percentage of AMIC stock owned by a 5% stockholder. &nbsp;Any person attempting such a transfer will be required, prior to the date of any proposed transfer, to request in writing that the board of directors review the proposed transfer and authorize or not authorize such proposed transfer. &nbsp;Any transfer attempted to be made in violation of the stock transfer restrictions will be null and void. &nbsp;In the event of an attempted or purported transfer involving a sale or disposition of capital stock in violation of stock transfer restrictions, the transferor shall remain the owner of such shares. &nbsp;Notwithstanding such transfer restrictions, there could be circumstances under which an issuance by AMIC of a significant number of new shares of Common Stock or other new class of equity security having certain characteristics (for example, the right to vote or convert into Common Stock) might result in an owne
rship change under the Code.</P>
<P style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>15. &nbsp;Insurance Reserves</B></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company maintains loss reserves to cover its estimated liability for unpaid losses and loss adjustment expenses, including legal and other fees and a portion of the Company's general expenses, for reported and unreported claims incurred as of the end of each accounting period. These loss reserves are based on actuarial assumptions and are maintained at levels that are in accordance with GAAP. Many factors could affect these reserves, including economic and social conditions, inflation, healthcare costs, changes in doctrines of legal liability and damage awards in litigation. Therefore, the Company's reserves are necessarily based on estimates, assumptions and analysis of historical experience. The Company's results depend upon the variation between actual claims experience and the assumptions used in determining reserves and pricing products. Reserve assumptions and estimates require significant judgment and, therefore, are inherent
ly uncertain. The Company cannot determine with precision the ultimate amounts that will be paid for actual claims or the timing of those payments.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt" align=center>66</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>Reserves are based on approved actuarial methods, but necessarily include assumptions about expenses, mortality, morbidity, lapse rates and future yield on related investments.</P>
<P style="margin:0pt" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt; font-family:Arial" align=justify>All of the Company's short-duration contracts are generated from our accident and health business, and are accounted for based on actuarial estimates of the amount of loss inherent in that period's claims, including losses incurred for which claims have not been reported. Short-duration contract loss estimates rely on actuarial observations of ultimate loss experience for similar historical events.</P>
